This guide exists to help Pivotal Cloud Foundry (PCF) Partners learn the high-level process of building and publishing a tile on Pivotal Network. 

For advanced developers with previous experience building tiles, see [Product Template Reference](./product-template-reference.html) and [Development Workflow Reference](./dev-workflow).

## <a id="tile-def"></a> What is a Tile?
Tiles are packaged software that can be integrated into PCF. 
Similar to how smartphone owners install apps on their phones, PCF operators and developers install tiles on PCF to access third-party services. The [GCP Service Broker for PCF](https://network.pivotal.io/products/gcp-service-broker) tile is an example of a third-party service available on PCF. 

To provide a service on PCF you can package your software into a tile with Tile Generator, a PCF tool. Once you have created a tile, you can publish it on Pivotal Network, the Pivotal tile marketplace.

###Tile Structure
Tiles are zipped directories with a ``.pivotal`` file extension.
Tile directories require three subdirectories: `metadata`, `migrations`, and `releases`. You can perform different actions within each subdirectory:

<table class="nice">
		<tr>
		<th>metadata</th>
		<td>Configure settings for your software in a YAML file. To see an example YAML file, see the <a href= "https://github.com/cf-platform-eng/tile-generator/blob/master/sample/tile.yml"> tile.yml file</a> in the tile-generator repo.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<th>migrations</th>
		<td>Track changes across different releases in a .js file. Only tiles with multiple releases use this subdirectory. Do not modify the files in this subdirectory during your first tile release. </td>	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<th>releases</th>
		<td>Deploy your service source code and other inputs for your build, such as a BOSH release. </td>
	</tr>
</table>  

Example tiles are published on [Pivotal Network](https://network.pivotal.io). You can download the example tiles and examine them locally to learn more about their structure. To see the file structure of a tile, do the following:

  1. Download a tile from Pivotal Network.
  1. Rename the file extension from ``.pivotal`` to ``.zip``.
  1. Unzip the file.

## <a id="tile-value"></a> Why Build a Tile?

There are multiple reasons to build and publish a tile on Pivotal Network. Tiles can help you:

* Find the widest possible audience for your service.
* Join a growing ecosystem that can easily integrate your service.
* Enable operators and app developers to interact with your service in an accessible and standardized way.

## <a id="tile-steps"></a> Building Your First Tile

There are two options for building your first tile. You can either attend partner days or develop independently. However, Pivotal strongly recommends attending Partner Days for hands-on guidance. 

