### <a id="develop"></a> Developing Independently

If you want to build a tile without attending Partner Days, the following procedure will minimize the learning curve for development. Pivotal engineers are always available through the Pivotal Partners Slack if you have any questions. However, creating a tile is a complex process and can be time consuming to complete on your own. Before performing the following procedure, Pivotal recommends that you set up the tools listed in [Toolkit](#toolkit).

#### 1. Figure out what to Build

There are several ways to package your software into a tile. If you use Tile Generator to package your software you also need to determine the inputs for your build before development. Inputs for you tile also depend on the service you are providing. Before starting development, [learn about the different tile types](https://docs.pivotal.io/tiledev/cf-concepts.html).

#### 2. Generate a Tile

Tile Generator is a tool that simplifies the building process for tiles. You input your software components (service broker, buildpacks, docker image etc.) into Tile Generator and the tool outputs a base tile. You can then configure this base tile based on your needs.

For information on setting up Tile Generator and building a base tile, see [Tile Generator](https://docs.pivotal.io/tiledev/tile-generator.html)

#### 3. Test your Tile

Before you publish your tile, you should manually test it using a Partner Integration Environment (PIE). In PIE you can see how the tile functions on an IaaS, such as Amazon Web Services or Google Cloud Platform. You can upload, configure and install your tile in PIE like an operator. 

To gain access to your PIE, reach out to your contact at Pivotal or [register as a partner](https://partners.pivotal.io/). 

If you already have access to your PIE, for information on how to log in, see [Shared PCF Development Environments](https://docs.pivotal.io/tiledev/2-2/environments.html)   

#### 4. Document your Tile

When you are ready to publish your tile, you should write documentation. Documentation is valuable for operators that use your tile. For more information on how to write and publish your documentation for PCF, see [Tile Documentation](https://docs.pivotal.io/tiledev/tile-documentation.html).

#### 5. Publish on Pivotal Network

 You can upload the first iteration of your tile to Pivotal Network, the Pivotal tile marketplace. You should reach out to your contact at Pivotal who can guide you through the process of uploading your tile to Pivotal Network. When you upload your tile on Pivotal Network, it becomes available for operators and developers to:

